"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, Scotty here. I am gonna walk you through the decay cycle of my garden today. So all the raised beds and all the vegetables, that's where the production side, the growth cycle is occurring. On the other side of my backyard, you'll see over right about there. That's a 50 gallon blue food grade drum. They run about $30 on the used market. I have no idea how much they cost on the new market. And my friend from Federal Grill, he's the manager there, has gotten his kitchen staff to put their organic matter, their uh onion skins and carrot cho and carrot uh greens and all these things into this barrel so I can compost them with wood chips that I get from generally just a tree service. I'll see one in the neighborhood and I'll stop it and I'll ask them to drop off a bunch of their uh wood chips into my driveway, and then I'll wheelchair or will wheelbarrow them off into this area, and I just feed it into that, and that's the carbon where the food waste is the nitrogen. You kind of mix those up and you get some really great compost. Over here, under the shade of the tree, which is very pleasant. I'm gonna get under here. This is my curing area. This is where the breakdown that happens over there is finished off. This is where the beetles and the earthworms and the nematodes and the protozoa and all the small and big little bugs that are completing the decay cycle come back into the process. Because when you hot compost, the thermophilic bacteria run all the other out life out while they're doing their business of breaking down the matter. Once it's broken down, you let it cure for another couple of months, preferably in the shade, and preferably with enough water before you put it in your garden. Anyway, that's the decay cycle of uh my garden. That's the half of it. Uh thanks.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody, Scotty here.\",\n      \"start\": 0.24,\n      \"end\": 2.16,\n      \"duration\": 1.92,\n      \"confi